\pard\sa180\f0\fs22\b 5. High-Level Architecture\b0\par
\pard\sa120\f2\fs20 +----------------------------+     +--------------------------+\par
| CRM customer data          |     | ADO onboarding signals   |\par
+----------------------------+     +--------------------------+\par
               \                /\par
                \              /\par
                 \            /\par
          +--------------------------------------+\par
          |      Know Me decision layer          |\par
          |  index.html + derived page logic     |\par
          +--------------------------------------+\par
                 /            \\par
                /              \\par
   +------------------------+   +-----------------------------+\par
   | Support insights JSON  |   | Power BI semantic insights  |\par
   +------------------------+   +-----------------------------+\par
\pard\sa180\f0\fs22 This decision layer produces a meeting-ready story rather than a flat data dump.\par

\pard\sa180\f0\fs22\b 6. Key Implementation Notes\b0\par
\pard\li360\sa100\fs22\bullet\tab EY semantic-model insights were added into the support-insight layer and rendered directly in Know Me\par
\pard\li360\sa100\fs22\bullet\tab A front-end binding bug in the Know Me update flow was fixed so selected customers now correctly resolve support insights\par
\pard\li360\sa100\fs22\bullet\tab ADO MCP was added and validated, but the page currently uses embedded onboarding signals rather than a live browser-side ADO call\par
\pard\li360\sa200\fs22\bullet\tab The onboarding status is currently rule-based and derived from customer fields already present in the local data\par

\pard\sa180\f0\fs22\b 7. Executive Takeaway\b0\par
\pard\sa120\f0\fs22 The Know Me tab is no longer just a place to look up customer information. It is now closer to a single-page service brief that combines customer context, support pressure, backlog shape, onboarding readiness, and next-action framing in one place. This is the right direction for leadership reviews, support escalations, and customer-facing preparation.\par
